In article <Cnp1Cs.716@chinet.chinet.com> schneier@chinet.chinet.com (Bruce Schneier) writes:


    Bruce> This question came up recently in a discussion.  Is there
    Bruce> any way to get a rough count of regular readers?

    Bruce> I've heard of something called "arbitron," which comiles a
    Bruce> count of people who subscribe to a given newsgroup and are
    Bruce> reasonably cought up.  Perhaps we can take a poll on a
    Bruce> hundred or so machines and assume that is a representitive
    Bruce> sample.

Jan '94 statistics posted to news.lists estimated the world readership
of sci.crypt at 90,000.

        +-- Estimated total number of people who read the group, worldwide.
        |     +-- Actual number of readers in sampled population
        |     |     +-- Propagation: how many sites receive this group at all
        |     |     |      +-- Recent traffic (messages per month)
        |     |     |      |      +-- Recent traffic (kilobytes per month)
        |     |     |      |      |      +-- Crossposting percentage
        |     |     |      |      |      |    +-- Cost ratio: $US/month/rdr
        |     |     |      |      |      |    |      +-- Share: % of newsrders
        |     |     |      |      |      |    |      |   who read this group.
        V     V     V      V      V      V    V      V
 224  90000  1096   79%   645  1623.6    18%  0.02   2.2%  sci.crypt

For the complete stats, look in:
rtfm.mit.edu:/pub/usenet/news.lists/USENET_Readership_report_for_Jan_94
                                   /USENET_READERSHIP_SUMMARY_REPORT_FOR_JAN_94

The statistical background is in the Summary file, the data in the actual report.

